{
  "title": "Refactoring CLI Tools Using FastAPI in Python 3.12+",
  "summary": "This guide demonstrates how to refactor Command Line Interface (CLI) tools using FastAPI, a modern, high-performance web framework for building APIs in Python 3.12+.",
  "key_points": [
    "FastAPI offers an easier and more efficient approach for creating CLI tools compared to traditional methods like argparse",
    "It allows you to leverage the power of web technologies such as routing, dependency injection, type hints, and OpenAPI documentation",
    "FastAPI can handle complex validation and serialization tasks, making your code cleaner and easier to maintain",
    "Integration with popular tools like Uvicorn (ASGI server) and Hypercorn (Quiche web server) allows for seamless deployment in various environments"
  ],
  "code_examples": [
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "from fastapi import FastAPI, CLIRunner\napp = FastAPI()\n@app.cli_router('/my-command')\ndef my_command():\n   print('Hello from FastAPI!')\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n   CLIRunner(app).run(\n      use_colors=True, argv=[\"myscript\", \"my-command\"])"
    }
  ],
  "version_notes": [
    "This example uses Python 3.12+ and FastAPI version 0.75.1",
    "For production purposes, it's recommended to use the latest stable versions of both packages"
  ],
  "caveats": [
    "While FastAPI provides an effective method for creating CLI tools, it may not always be the best choice when simplicity and low overhead are critical. Traditional CLI libraries like argparse might still be preferred in such scenarios",
    "It's essential to consider the size of your project and its specific requirements before deciding whether to use FastAPI or more traditional methods"
  ]
}

code_examples.code:
from fastapi import FastAPI, CLIRunner
app = FastAPI()
@app.cli_router('/my-command')
def my_command():
   print('Hello from FastAPI!')
if __name__ == '__main__':
   CLIRunner(app).run(
      use_colors=True, argv=["myscript", "my-command"])
